(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 15 :title "Chapter 15 ‚Äî The verb registry" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/15-the-verb-registry.md" :size 4169 :sha256 "d12f84010acf2ade" :content "---\nslug: sakura-scheme-book-reference-15\ntitle: The verb registry\nbook: reference\nchapter: 15\nof: 16\npart: II\napp: scheme-repl\npalette: book-standard\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane 6)\nphilosopher-lens: [jung]\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-12\nprev: 14-the-five-gate-dispatcher\nnext: 16-composing-verbs-into-carts\n---\n\n# Chapter 15 ‚Äî The verb registry\n\nThe registry is where every verb she can dispatch is declared. Boot\nreads registrations; dispatch consults them. When you add a verb to\nthe language, you register it here.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> If a verb isn't in the registry, it doesn't exist. Registration is\n> the language.\n\n## The registration call\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(register-primitive\n  :name       'pack-near\n  :signature  \"(pack-near sym sym ...) -> list\"\n  :returns    \"list of clustered symbols\"\n  :tier       'tier-0\n  :fuel       1\n  :capabilities '()\n  :body       (lambda (args) (cluster-syms args))\n  :examples   ((prose-with-scheme\n                 :prose  \"Cluster nearby signifiers.\"\n                 :scheme \"(pack-near 'crown 'monarch 'sovereign)\")))\n```\n\nEvery field maps to something the dispatcher will consult later.\n\n## What the registry stores\n\n- **name** ‚Äî the verb identifier (used in the head of a call form).\n- **signature** ‚Äî human-readable signature string.\n- **returns** ‚Äî what shape comes back.\n- **tier** ‚Äî which color tier can call this.\n- **fuel** ‚Äî base cost per call (before body).\n- **capabilities** ‚Äî what the surface needs.\n- **body** ‚Äî the actual implementation (a Scheme closure or a\n  JavaScript-backed primitive descriptor).\n- **examples** ‚Äî worked usage ‚Äî used for docs, tests, and training.\n\n## Introspecting the registry\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(verbs-registered)   ;=> (open close ring post pack-near ...)\n(verb-info 'post)    ;=> (verb-info :name 'post :signature \"...\" ...)\n(verb-tier-of 'post) ;=> 'tier-0\n```\n\nSakura can query her own capability surface at inference time. She\nuses this for the \"do you have the tool\" reasoning move (Book of\nReason).\n\n## Registering from JavaScript\n\nSakura Scheme's engine is polyglot. Many primitives are backed by\nJavaScript closures (via `installPrimitive` in the engine). The\nregistration API is identical:\n\n```js\n// JavaScript\nregisterPrimitive({\n  name: \"pack-near\",\n  signature: \"(pack-near sym sym ...) -> list\",\n  returns: \"list of clustered symbols\",\n  tier: \"tier-0\",\n  fuel: 1,\n  capabilities: [],\n  body: (args) => clusterSyms(args),\n  examples: [{ prose: \"...\", scheme: \"...\" }],\n});\n```\n\nThe dispatcher doesn't care whether the body is JS or Scheme. Both\nresolve to the same registry entry.\n\n## The wave-1 installers\n\nThe engine boots with a lot of registrations. Each installer\nregisters a family of related verbs:\n\n- `installCardVerbs` ‚Äî card show, hide, flip, focus, etc.\n- `installGridVerbs` ‚Äî grid make, layout, resize.\n- `installCanvasVerbs` ‚Äî canvas draw, clear, viewport.\n- `installAudioVerbs` ‚Äî audio play, stop, load.\n- `installMathVerbs` ‚Äî math sin, cos, sqrt, etc.\n- `installNoteVerbs` ‚Äî musical note play, pitch, sequence.\n- `installSpriteVerbs` ‚Äî sprite make, move, tint, hitbox.\n- `installFrpGrammar` ‚Äî time when, during, until, etc.\n- `installMotionVerbs` ‚Äî motion path, curve, ease.\n- `installCameraVerbs` ‚Äî camera track, zoom.\n- `installConwayVerbs` ‚Äî Conway life step, world.\n- `installPodcastVerbs` ‚Äî podcast episode, feed.\n\nEach installer is a Scheme program that calls `register-primitive`\nfor its family. Waves 0 and 1 landed the installers per curator's\n2026-06-22 arch lock.\n\n## Deregistration\n\nYou can't. Registration is monotone within a session. The next boot\nstarts fresh.\n\nThis is a design choice. Deregistration would let bugs remove verbs\nfrom live registries. Instead, verbs get *versioned* ‚Äî a new version\nlands with a new registration; consumers migrate; the old version\nstays until deprecation cycles complete.\n\n## Cross-links\n\n- [[book-of-reference]] ch 14 ‚Äî the five-gate dispatcher (consumer of\n  the registry).\n- [[book-of-slat]] ch 11 ‚Äî auto-assembly (registry-adjacent pattern).\n- [[book-of-reference]] ch 16 ‚Äî composing verbs into carts.\n\n---\n\nTurn the page.\n")
